04272nam a22006375i 9780271071350DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20211986pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710713507 a10.1515/97802710713502doi  a(DE-B1597)583740  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a1932231 aKrell, David Farrell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIntimations of Mortality :bTime, Truth, and Finitude in Heidegger's Thinking of Being /cDavid Farrell Krell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1986  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations of Works Cited -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Intimations of Time and Being -- tPart Two. Intimations of Truth and Turning -- tPart Three. Intimations of a History of Being -- tPart Four. Intimations of Mortality -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHeidegger's thinking has an underlying unity, this book argues, and has cogency for seemingly diverse domains of modern culture: philosophy and religion, aesthetics and literary criticism, intellectual history and social theory. "The theme of mortality-finite human existence-pervades Heidegger's thought," in the author's words, "before, during, and after his magnum opus, Being and Times, published in 1927." This theme is manifested in Heidegger's work not "as funereal melodramatics or as despair and destructive nihilism" but rather "as a thinking within anxiety." Four major subthemes in Heidegger's thinking are explored in the book's four parts: the fundamental ontology developed in Being and Time; the "lighting and clearing" of Being, understood as "unconcealment"; the history of philosophy-with emphasis on Heraclitus, Hegel, and Nietzsche-interpreted as the "destiny" of Being; and the poetics of Being, explicated as the "fundamental experience" of mortality. Neither an introduction nor a survey, this book is a close reading of a wide range of Heidegger's books, lectures, and articles-including extensive material not yet translated into English-informed by the author's conversations with Heidegger in 1974-76. Each of the four subthemes is treated critically. The aim of the book is to push its interrogations of Heidegger's thought as far as possible, in order to help the reader toward an independent assessment of his work and to encourage novel, radically conceived approaches to traditional philosophical problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aOntologyxHistoryx20th century. 0aOntologyxHistoryy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271071350zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271071350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271071350/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK